Every student in the WordPress Credits program creates a public project website.
This is not a random blog or a personal website about any unrelated topic.
Instead, it is a structured learning journal documenting the student’s journey through the WordPress Credits curriculum.

Think of it as your portfolio + progress log + reflection space, all in one.

⸻

✅ Purpose of the Project Website

Your project website should:

1. Document your weekly progress

Follow the structure of the lessons on the official course:
📌 https://learn.wordpress.org/course/wordpress-credits/

Each time you complete a lesson module, publish a short post summarizing:
	•	What you learned
	•	What was new or surprising
	•	What skills you practiced
	•	What contribution tasks you completed
	•	What challenges you faced and how you solved them

2. Show your growing understanding of the WordPress ecosystem

Examples of topics you may write about:
	•	What open source means and why it matters
	•	What the WordPress community looks like
	•	What contribution areas exist (Core, Docs, Design, Polyglots, etc.)
	•	Which teams you explored and why you chose your preferred one

3. Reflect on your personal development

Your mentors want to see:
	•	Your increasing technical or creative confidence
	•	Your collaboration with others
	•	Your problem-solving strategies
	•	Your communication style
	•	Your contribution history and work habits

4. Serve as a portfolio piece

At the end of the program:
	•	You can share your website with future employers
	•	It becomes proof of your contribution experience
	•	It showcases your growth, writing skills, and consistency

