🚫 What the Project Website Should Not Be
	•	Not a cooking blog
	•	Not a website about your hobbies
	•	Not a random business concept
	•	Not unrelated school assignments
	•	Not a generic website built “just because”

Your website must have a single purpose:
👉 Document your WordPress Credits journey.

You may make it visually unique or add personal design touches,
but the content must follow the course progression.

⸻

📚 Recommended Structure (Students Can Follow This Template)

Homepage
	•	A short introduction: “I am a student participating in the WordPress Credits Program.”
	•	A summary of what the site will document.

Posts (One per lesson/module)

Suggested titles:
	1.	Lesson 1 — Introduction to Open Source & WordPress
	2.	Lesson 2 — Understanding the WordPress Community
	3.	Lesson 3 — Exploring Contribution Areas
	4.	Lesson 4 — Joining WordPress Slack & Getting Started
	5.	Lesson 5 — Choosing My Contribution Area
	6.	Lesson 6 — First Contributions & Feedback
	7.	Weekly Contribution Logs
	8.	Final Reflection & What I Learned

Final Summary Page
	•	What I accomplished
	•	What I contributed
	•	My biggest challenges
	•	Skills gained
	•	What I want to do next as a contributor

⸻

🎯 In One Sentence

Your project website is a public learning journal that tells the story of your WordPress Credits journey — step by step, lesson by lesson — and demonstrates your growth as a contributor.
